        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-10-23T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-10-23T08:00:00-05:00" n="320"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d320">
                <head>320. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the United
                        Kingdom</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d320fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 882.10/10–2358. Secret; Priority. Repeated to Paris for <gloss
                            target="#t_USRO1">USRO</gloss>, Ankara, and Bonn.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>London</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1958-10-23T13:00:00+00:00">October 23, 1958, 1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2221. From <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName>.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d320fn1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> was in London for discussions
                        with the U.K. Government about the future of a European free trade
                        area.</note> In conversation with <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName> this morning accompanied by Ambassador Whitney I
                    mentioned Turkish interest rate problem and told <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName> I thought it was vitally important for political
                    reasons to make some gesture to Turks which would give Turkish Government reason
                    for accepting relatively high rate of interest. I said that if <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> could agree on 5-3/4 percent rate and at same
                    time make statement that if they were making a loan of similar size and duration
                    to a Commonwealth country at this time the rate would be 5-3/4 percent Turkish
                    Government would then have a valid reason for accepting. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName> had obviously been briefed on this
                    subject and while there was no commitment I had definite impression that we will
                    be able reach agreement along these lines since <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName> offered no objection to procedure as outlined.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d320fn2">No final decision was taken at the October 23–25
                        meeting of the creditor nations on the interest rate.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName>Whitney</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
